wgaPsykologiuModig kwgaLekuLevande leksaker saVara snälluSnäll kwgaPsykologiuSnäll kwhaFlygplatseruResor kwhaUpptäcktsresoruResor kwhaUndervattensresoruResor kwhaFlygresoruResor kwhaSkolresoruResor kwhaTurismuResor kwhaCharterresoruResor kwhaBussresoruResor kwhaSafariuResor kwhaÄventyrareuResor kwhaTågresoruResor kwhaUpptäcktsresandeuResor kwhaBallongresoruResor kwhaJordenruntresoruResor kwhaFripassagerareuResor kwhaTågluffninguResor kwhaJärnvägsstationeruResor kwhaBåtresoruResor kwhaBadorteruResor kwhaLiftauResor kwhaBilresoruResor kwhaSpråkresoruResor saVara nyfikenuNyfiken kwgaPsykologiuNyfiken kwgaÖvernaturliga väsenuFörmänskligade djur kaSmåbarnsbilderböckeruBilderböcker kaPekböckeruBilderböcker kaKartongböckeruBilderböcker saUngdomslitteraturuBarn- och ungdomslitteratur kaUngdomsböckeruBarn- och ungdomslitteratur kaMellanåldersböckeruBarn- och ungdomslitteratur kaKapitelböckeruBarn- och ungdomslitteratur kaBilderböckeruBarn- och ungdomslitteratur  5Sax  ab260108||0000|||||000||||||000000eu  5SbShSv2026j107xnb2026monxfatkla  5Sa{"@id":"g27f3vnjdd1tx2xw","modified":"2026-01-08T11:04:55.345+01:00"}2librisxl04628cam a22005775i sdkrgngnq6qj8psbSE-LIBR20260108112502.0260108s2025    nyu||||||b||||001 0|eng|   a2025015957  aGBC5967292bnb7 a3006055922Uk  a9780197785027qhardback  a0197785026  z9780197785034  z9780197785041  z9780197785058  qepubz9780197785034z9780197785041z97801977850588 aCIPO000281252  a(OCoLC)on1512065214  aSbengcDLCdIG#dYDXdOCLCOdUKMGBdOCLCOdBDXdSeierda  aeng  apcc 0aB279800a193223/eng/2025061310aColonialism and Enlightenment :bthe legacy of German race theories /c[Bettina Brandt, Daniel L. Purdy, editors].  a2509 1aNew York, NY, United States of America.bOxford University Press,c[2025]  a312 pagesbillustrations (black and white)c24 cm  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  avolumebnc2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.  a"The shock American scholars felt at rediscovering that Immanuel Kant, the cosmopolitan defender of universal rights, had also written several essays delineating racial classifications based on skin color has had lasting consequences. The tumult has been unrelenting: how could the defender of human rights also espouse racial prejudice? Reviewing this heated discussion, our volume includes scholars who long have had a voice in these debates, as well as younger academics, who have been trained in critical race theory. The work of our contributors reflects their diverse backgrounds, ranging across philosophy, German studies, African-American studies, post-colonialism, and African literature. Our volume includes decisive essays that reveal the historical sources in modern racial thinking. We explain the long-term consequences of German colonial discourse in particular how the discourse around becoming "white" and "German" has persisted across centuries. For the last 30 years, scholars treated the Enlightenment race theory and nineteenth-century German colonialism as two distinct events. This volume will demonstrate that from its first formulations in the eighteenth century and well into the twentieth century, German race theory was implicated in colonialism to the extent that philosophers and biologists drew their arguments about race from information that was generated by the slave trade and plantation economies in the Americas. Without colonialism and slavery, it would not have been possible for German professors to initiate a discourse on race as they did in the eighteenth century. The chapters in Colonialism and Enlightenment explore how eighteenth-century German theories about race reinforced discourses on colonial settlements, both within and outside Europe. Given the multiple, often contradictory positions developed in the Enlightenment, we explore how later race thinkers responded to earlier formulations. How did Enlightenment debates figure in later racisms? How did nationalist and Nazi racisms view Enlightenment anthropology? What Enlightenment concepts and configurations persisted into the twentieth century? Our contributors do not take a narrow position within these controversies. Instead, we present a variety of positions, as we take stock of the debates about race and Enlightenment held over the last 30 years"-- Provided by publisher.  aImported from: zcat.oclc.org:210/OLUCWorldCat (Do not remove)10aKant, Immanuel,d1724-1804 0aRacism. 0aRacexPhilosophy. 6aRacexPhilosophie. 7aEnlightenment2fast 7aGermany2fast1 aBrandt, Bettina4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPurdy, Daniel L.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iOnline versiontColonialism and EnlightenmentdNew York, NY, United States of America. : Oxford University Press, [2025]z9780197785034  asingle unitbmono  abibliographybbibliography  aindexbindex  a{"@id":"sdkrgngnq6qj8psb","modified":"2026-01-08T11:25:02.016+01:00"}2librisxl  5Sax  ab260108||0000|||||000||||||000000eu  5SbShORDER 260108/adlib ABON UNDER INKÖPiBeställdxjn  5Sa{"@id":"vgmtjrknsqlqfwg4","modified":"2026-01-08T11:25:24.513+01:00"}2librisxl02183cac a22006253i d05c3glmbm9bbbbbSE-LIBR20260108125521.0260108i20249999sw |||||||||||000 ||swe|c  aSbsweeierda  aswe2 aEr resa4isb10aEr resa - samling av trycksaker 0c2024-9999  atextbtxt2rdacontent  aunmediatedbn2rdamedia  asheetbnb2rdacarrier 7aResebyråer0https://id.kb.se/term/sao/Resebyr%C3%A5er2sao 7aResor0https://id.kb.se/term/sao/Resor2sao  a{"@id":"d05c3glmbm9bbbbb","modified":"2026-01-08T12:55:21.972+01:00"}2librisxl kwhaKaravaneruResor kwhaSällskapsresoruResor kwhaResor med barnuResor kwhaBildningsresoruResor kwhaBussresoruResor kwhaTjänsteresoruResor kwhaReseha