y, Niall Oddy explores representations of Europe in sixteenth and early-seventeenth century French writing to argue that Europe as an idea evolved in productive dialogue with emerging national consciousness, not as an alternative to the nation state. Analysing literary texts alongside works of travel, geography, history and politics, this book demonstrates how ideas of Europe were shaped by real and imagined journeys across the globe and adapted across a range of discursive contexts for varied purposes. Using the notion of 'imagined geography' to present a conceptual map of what Europe looked like from different points across the globe, each chapter examines representations of the continent through the lens of one location (Brazil, Constantinople, Malta, Geneva). In a period of great intellectual transformation, as new interactions with cultures overseas reshaped how the wider world was understood, this focus on nationhood uncovers how, as the idea of 'Europe' developed, it emerged as a contested notion and an issue of debate.  aIn English  aImported from: zcat.oclc.org:210/OLUCWorldCat (Do not remove) 7a1500-talet0https://id.kb.se/term/sao/1500-talet2sao 7a1600-talet0https://id.kb.se/term/sao/1600-talet2sao 7aRenässansen0https://id.kb.se/term/sao/Ren%C3%A4ssansen2sao 7aReseskildringar0https://id.kb.se/term/sao/Reseskildringar2sao 7aLitteraturxhistoria0https://id.kb.se/term/sao/Litteratur--historia2sao 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh 4aLiterary Studies. 7aEuropa0https://id.kb.se/term/sao/Europa2sao 7aFrankrike0https://id.kb.se/term/sao/Frankrike2sao  a{"@id":"8v18dlnh6q4sk255","modified":"2026-01-08T14:32:11.552+01:00"}2librisxl saFemtonhundrataletu1500-talet saSextonde århundradetu1500-talet saSextonhundrataletu1600-talet saSjuttonde århundradetu1600-talet sw||eaLitteraturhistoriauLitteraturxhistoria saVästerländsk litteraturhistoriauLitteraturxhistoria kwhaMedeltidslitteraturuLitteraturxhisto